<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10066c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10066c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10066c"> 66(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> changing effigy of stamp</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La nouvelle loi sur le port des lettres re&ccedil;ues des d&eacute;partements &agrave; Paris, portant la petite vignette carr&eacute;e, signe de l&apos;affranchissement. <mark>Cette vignette est &agrave; l&apos;effigie de la R&eacute;publique, se d&eacute;tachant en blanc sur fond noir</mark>. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Le second type de la R&eacute;publique de 1848 conserva bien la m&ecirc;me indication de la forme du Gouvernement, mais la <mark>Libert&eacute;</mark> fut remplac&eacute;e dans le cadre du timbre par <mark>l&apos;effigie du Prince-Pr&eacute;sident Louis-Napol&eacute;on</mark>, &eacute;lu pr&eacute;sident le 10 d&eacute;cembre 1851. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> En 1866, l&apos;effigie des timbres fut laur&eacute;e; puis vint la p&eacute;riode des essais. <font color="green">[The new law for the carriage of letters arriving in Paris from the d&eacute;partements carried the small square vignette, the sign of stamping. This vignette has the effigy of the Republic picked out in white on a black background.[&hellip;]</font> The Second Republic of 1848 did retain the same indication of the form of government but in the stamp the figure of Liberty was replaced with an effigy of Prince-President Louis Napoleon, who was elected President on December 10, 1851.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> In 1866, the effigy on the stamps was adorned with laurels, then came the trial period.] <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 282ff</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
